Here is an example of automatically generating a table of contents in a LATEX document:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft} % For customizing the table of contents

\usepackage{hyperref} % For hyperlinks in the PDF

\setcounter{tocdepth}{2} % Show sections and subsections in the TOC

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Prints the table of contents

\section{Section 1} 
\subsection{Subsection 1} 
\subsubsection{Subsubsection 1} 

\section{Section 2}
\subsection{Subsection 2}

\section{Section 3}  

\end{document}

The key commands here are:

\usepackage{tocloft} - Loads the tocloft package which customizes the table of contents.

\setcounter{tocdepth}{2} - Sets the depth of the table of contents to show sections and subsections.

\tableofcontents - Prints the table of contents at the point in the document where this command is placed.

\section{} - Used to define sections, which are then automatically added to the table of contents.

\subsection{} - Used to define subsections, which are then automatically added to the table of contents.

The table of contents is automatically generated from the sectioning commands used in the document. The tocloft package and \setcounter{tocdepth} command simply provide some customization for the table of contents.

Here is a LATEX code to draw a chessboard based on a FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

\tikzstyle{square} = [draw, thick, fill=white!60!black] 
\tikzstyle{highlight} = [fill=yellow!80!black]

\begin{center}
\begin{chessboard}
\chessboardsquares
\chessboard[FEN = "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
\end{chessboard}
\end{center}

\end{document} 
```

This does the following:

- Loads the chessboard and other useful packages 
- Defines TikZ styles for squares and highlight
- Centers the board
- Uses the \chessboardsquares command to draw the empty board 
- Uses \chessboard with the FEN string to place pieces on the board
- The w KQkq - 0 1 at the end of the FEN string is meta info we don't use here

So you can replace the FEN string with any position you want to draw the board for. Let me know if you have any other questions!

